			<h2 class="heading-large">What are your responsibilities?</h2>

            <p>When you employ an apprentice, you’re agreeing to provide:</p>
            <ul class="list-bullet">
                <li>meaningful work</li>
                <li>a salary</li>
                <li>time to train</li>
                <li>an employment contract</li>
                <li>an apprenticeship agreement</li>
                <li>a statement of commitment</li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="heading-medium">Pay and conditions</h3>

            <p>You must pay your apprentice at least £2.73 an hour. Most employers choose to pay more than this.</p>
            <p>If they’re 19 or older and have completed the first year of their apprenticeship, they’re entitled to <a href="#">national minimum wage</a>.</p>

            <h3 class="heading-medium">Training</h3>

            <p>Apprentices need paid time off for training.</p>
            <p>This includes any extra time for English and maths study, or support if they have disabilities or learning difficulties.</p>

            <h3 class="heading-medium">Hours</h3>

            <p>Most apprentices spend at least 30 hours a week with their employers. They must work for at least 16.</p>
            <p>They should be able to complete their apprenticeships inside their contracted hours.</p>

